<div class=3D"shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=
=3D"display:none">Nonparametric test of the null hypothesis</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">"Wilcoxon ra=
nk-sum test" redirects here. For Wilcoxon signed-rank test, see <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilcoxon_signed-rank_test" title=3D"Wilcoxon =
signed-rank test">Wilcoxon signed-rank test</a>.</div>
<p>The <b>Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-ele=
ment-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" st=
yle=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" a=
lttext=3D"{\displaystyle U}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>U</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle U}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/458a728f53b9a0274f059cd695e067c430956025" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.783ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle U}"=
></span> test</b> (also called the <b>Mann=E2=80=93Whitney=E2=80=93Wilcoxon=
</b> (<b>MWW/MWU</b>), <b>Wilcoxon rank-sum test</b>, or <b>Wilcoxon=E2=80=
=93Mann=E2=80=93Whitney test</b>) is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Nonparametric_statistics" title=3D"Nonparametric statistics">nonparame=
tric</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_test" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical test">statistical test</a> of the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Null_hypothesis" title=3D"Null hypoth=
esis">null hypothesis</a> that randomly selected values <i>X</i> and <i>Y</=
i> from two populations have the same distribution.=20
</p><p>Nonparametric tests used on two <i>dependent</i> samples are the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sign_test" title=3D"Sign test">sign t=
est</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilcoxon_signed-ra=
nk_test" title=3D"Wilcoxon signed-rank test">Wilcoxon signed-rank test</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Assumptions_and_formal_stat=
ement_of_hypotheses">Assumptions and formal statement of hypotheses</h2><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span>=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMann%E2%80%93Whitne=
y_U_test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Assumpti=
ons and formal statement of hypotheses"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Although <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Mann" title=3D"H=
enry Mann">Henry Mann</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dona=
ld_Ransom_Whitney" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Donald Ransom Whitney">Do=
nald Ransom Whitney</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-mannwhitney1947_1-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_te=
st#cite_note-mannwhitney1947-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> developed the Mann=E2=80=93Whitn=
ey <i>U</i> test under the assumption of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Continuous_probability_distribution" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Continuous probability distribution">continuous</a> responses with the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alternative_hypothesis" title=3D"Alter=
native hypothesis">alternative hypothesis</a> being that one distribution i=
s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stochastic_ordering" title=3D"St=
ochastic ordering">stochastically greater</a> than the other, there are man=
y other ways to formulate the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Null=
_hypothesis" title=3D"Null hypothesis">null</a> and alternative hypotheses =
such that the Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test will give a valid test.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-FayProschan2010_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-FayProschan20=
10-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p><p>A very general formulation is to assume that:
</p>
<ol><li>All the observations from both groups are <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_independence" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"St=
atistical independence">independent</a> of each other,</li>
<li>The responses are at least <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ord=
inal_measurement" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ordinal measurement">ordin=
al</a> (i.e., one can at least say, of any two observations, which is the g=
reater),</li>
<li>Under the null hypothesis <i>H</i><sub>0</sub>, the distributions of bo=
th populations are identical.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note=
-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup></li>
<li>The alternative hypothesis <i>H</i><sub>1</sub> is that the distributio=
ns are not identical.</li></ol>
<p>Under the general formulation, the test is only <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Consistency_(statistics)#Tests" title=3D"Consistency (stat=
istics)">consistent</a> when the following occurs under <i>H</i><sub>1</sub=
>:
</p>
<ol><li>The probability of an observation from population <i>X</i> exceedin=
g an observation from population <i>Y</i> is different (larger, or smaller)=
 than the probability of an observation from <i>Y</i> exceeding an observat=
ion from <i>X</i>; i.e.,  <span class=3D"texhtml">P(<i>X</i> &gt; <i>Y</i>)=
 =E2=89=A0 P(<i>Y</i> &gt; <i>X</i>)</span> or <span class=3D"texhtml">P(<i=
>X</i> &gt; <i>Y</i>) + 0.5 =C2=B7 P(<i>X</i> =3D <i>Y</i>) =E2=89=A0 0.5</=
span>.</li></ol>
<p>Under more strict assumptions than the general formulation above, e.g., =
if the responses are assumed to be continuous and the alternative is restri=
cted to a shift in location, i.e., <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub>1</=
sub>(<i>x</i>) =3D <i>F</i><sub>2</sub>(<i>x</i> + <i>=CE=B4</i>)</span>, w=
e can interpret a significant Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test as showing=
 a difference in medians. Under this location shift assumption, we can also=
 interpret the Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test as assessing whether the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hodges%E2%80%93Lehmann_estimate" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hodges=E2=80=93Lehmann estimate">Hodges=E2=80=
=93Lehmann estimate</a> of the difference in central tendency between the t=
wo populations differs from zero. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Hodges%E2%80%93Lehmann_estimate" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hodges=
=E2=80=93Lehmann estimate">Hodges=E2=80=93Lehmann estimate</a> for this two=
-sample problem is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Median" tit=
le=3D"Median">median</a> of all possible differences between an observation=
 in the first sample and an observation in the second sample.
</p><p>Otherwise, if both the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stat=
istical_dispersion" title=3D"Statistical dispersion">dispersions</a> and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shape_parameter" title=3D"Shape para=
meter">shapes</a> of the distribution of both samples differ, the Mann=E2=
=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test fails a test of medians. It is possible to show=
 examples where medians are numerically equal while the test rejects the nu=
ll hypothesis with a small p-value.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cit=
e_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-5"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>The Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test / Wilcoxon rank-sum test is n=
ot the same as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilcoxon_signed=
-rank_test" title=3D"Wilcoxon signed-rank test">Wilcoxon <i>signed</i>-rank=
 test</a>, although both are nonparametric and involve summation of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ranking_(statistics)" title=3D"Ranking (s=
tatistics)">ranks</a>. The Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test is applied to=
 independent samples. The Wilcoxon signed-rank test is applied to matched o=
r dependent samples.
</p>
