      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle M=3D{1 \over =
c(c-1)}\sum \mathrm {AUC} _{k,\ell }}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/9b6a0777946207b4dd090063314aa19147bfbd9d" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.671ex; width:25.728ex; height:6.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle M=
=3D{1 \over c(c-1)}\sum \mathrm {AUC} _{k,\ell }}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>Where <i>c</i> is the number of classes, and the <i>R</i><sub><i>k</i>,<=
i>=E2=84=93</i></sub> term of AUC<sub><i>k</i>,<i>=E2=84=93</i></sub> consi=
ders only the ranking of the items belonging to classes <i>k</i> and <i>=E2=
=84=93</i> (i.e., items belonging to all other classes are ignored) accordi=
ng to the classifier's estimates of the probability of those items belongin=
g to class <i>k</i>. AUC<sub><i>k</i>,<i>k</i></sub> will always be zero bu=
t, unlike in the two-class case, generally <span class=3D"texhtml">AUC<sub>=
<i>k</i>,<i>=E2=84=93</i></sub> =E2=89=A0 AUC<sub><i>=E2=84=93</i>,<i>k</i>=
</sub></span>, which is why the <i>M</i> measure sums over all (<i>k</i>,<i=
>=E2=84=93</i>) pairs, in effect using the average of AUC<sub><i>k</i>,<i>=
=E2=84=93</i></sub> and AUC<sub><i>=E2=84=93</i>,<i>k</i></sub>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Calculations">Calculations<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMann%E2%80%9=
3Whitney_U_test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: C=
alculations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<p>The test involves the calculation of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Statistic" title=3D"Statistic">statistic</a>, usually called <i>U</=
i>, whose distribution under the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/N=
ull_hypothesis" title=3D"Null hypothesis">null hypothesis</a> is known:
</p>
<ul><li>In the case of small samples, the distribution is tabulated</li>
<li>For sample sizes above&nbsp;~20, approximation using the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distributio=
n">normal distribution</a> is fairly good.</li></ul>
<p>Alternatively, the null distribution can be approximated using <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permutation_test" title=3D"Permutation te=
st">permutation tests</a> and Monte Carlo simulations.
</p><p>Some books tabulate statistics equivalent to <i>U</i>, such as the s=
um of ranks in one of the samples, rather than <i>U</i> itself.
</p><p>The Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test is included in most <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_statistical_packages" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"List of statistical packages">statistical packages</a>.=
=20
</p><p>It is also easily calculated by hand, especially for small samples. =
There are two ways of doing this.
</p><p><b>Method one:</b>
</p><p>For comparing two small sets of observations, a direct method is qui=
ck, and gives insight into the meaning of the <i>U</i> statistic, which cor=
responds to the number of wins out of all pairwise contests (see the tortoi=
se and hare example under Examples below). For each observation in one set,=
 count the number of times this first value wins over any observations in t=
he other set (the other value loses if this first is larger). Count&nbsp;0.=
5 for any ties. The sum of wins and ties is <i>U</i> (i.e.: <span class=3D"=
mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-in=
line mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://w=
ww.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle U_{1}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>U</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle U_{1}}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/bc9e7f892894bc50c32ce1b9f9a68a15562146ac" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:2.642ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle U_{=
1}}"></span>) for the first set. <i>U</i> for the other set is the converse=
 (i.e.: <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e U_{2}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>U</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle U_{2}}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/590fa6a550fbe2866a28243a733d54245d218b9d" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:2.642ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle U_{=
2}}"></span>).
</p><p><b>Method two:</b>
</p><p>For larger samples:
</p>
<ol><li>Assign numeric ranks to all the observations (put the observations =
from both groups to one set), beginning with 1 for the smallest value. Wher=
e there are groups of tied values, assign a rank equal to the midpoint of u=
nadjusted rankings (e.g., the ranks of <span class=3D"texhtml">(3, 5, 5, 5,=
 5, 8)</span> are <span class=3D"texhtml">(1, 3.5, 3.5, 3.5, 3.5, 6)</span>=
, where the unadjusted ranks would be <span class=3D"texhtml">(1, 2, 3, 4, =
5, 6)</span>).</li>
<li>Now, add up the ranks for the observations which came from sample&nbsp;=
1. The sum of ranks in sample 2 is now determined, since the sum of all the=
 ranks equals <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>N</i>(<i>N</i> + 1)/2</span> where=
 <i>N</i> is the total number of observations.</li>
<li><i>U</i> is then given by:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_no=
te-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup></li></ol>
<dl><dd><dl><dd><dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-in=
line"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"=
display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=
=3D"{\displaystyle U_{1}=3DR_{1}-{n_{1}(n_{1}+1) \over 2}\,\!}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
