    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>U</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>i</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>n</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <msub>
          <mi>n</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle U_{i}=3Dn_{1}=
n_{2}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/189de53db240b029893b7258ab7b2cfc978f92be" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:10.384ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle U_=
{i}=3Dn_{1}n_{2}}"></span>). In such a case, the "other" <i>U</i> would be&=
nbsp;0.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Examples">Examples</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMann%E2%80%93Whitney=
_U_test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Examples"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Illustration_of_calculation=
_methods">Illustration of calculation methods</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Illustration of calculation me=
thods"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span>=
</span></div>
<p>Suppose that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aesop" title=3D"Ae=
sop">Aesop</a> is dissatisfied with his <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/The_Tortoise_and_the_Hare" title=3D"The Tortoise and the Hare">classi=
c experiment</a> in which one <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tort=
oise" title=3D"Tortoise">tortoise</a> was found to beat one <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hare" title=3D"Hare">hare</a> in a race, and deci=
des to carry out a significance test to discover whether the results could =
be extended to tortoises and hares in general. He collects a sample of 6 to=
rtoises and 6 hares, and makes them all run his race at once. The order in =
which they reach the finishing post (their rank order, from first to last c=
rossing the finish line) is as follows, writing T for a tortoise and H for =
a hare:
</p>
<dl><dd>T H H H H H T T T T T H</dd></dl>
<p>What is the value of <i>U</i>?
</p>
<ul><li>Using the direct method, we take each tortoise in turn, and count t=
he number of hares it beats, getting 6, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, which means that <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><i>U<sub>T</sub></i> =3D 11</span>. Alternatively, we =
could take each hare in turn, and count the number of tortoises it beats. I=
n this case, we get 5, 5, 5, 5, 5, 0, so <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>U<sub>H=
</sub></i> =3D 25</span>. Note that the sum of these two values for <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><i>U</i> =3D 36</span>, which is <span class=3D"texhtml">6=
=C3=976</span>.</li>
<li>Using the indirect method:</li></ul>
<dl><dd>Rank the animals by the time they take to complete the course, so g=
ive the first animal home rank 12, the second rank 11, and so forth.</dd>
<dd>The sum of the ranks achieved by the tortoises is <span class=3D"texhtm=
l">12 + 6 + 5 + 4 + 3 + 2 =3D 32</span>.
<dl><dd>Therefore <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>U<sub>T</sub></i> =3D 32 =E2=
=88=92 (6=C3=977)/2 =3D 32 =E2=88=92 21 =3D 11</span> (same as method one).=
</dd>
<dd>The sum of the ranks achieved by the hares is <span class=3D"texhtml">1=
1 + 10 + 9 + 8 + 7 + 1 =3D 46</span>, leading to <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>U<sub>H</sub></i> =3D 46 =E2=88=92 21 =3D 25</span>.</dd></dl></dd></dl>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Example_statement_of_result=
s">Example statement of results</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DMann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;secti=
on=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Example statement of results"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In reporting the results of a Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test, it is =
important to state:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-12"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>A measure of the central tendencies of the two groups (means or med=
ians; since the Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test is an ordinal test, medi=
ans are usually recommended)</li>
<li>The value of <i>U</i> (perhaps with some measure of effect size, such a=
s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#Comm=
on_language_effect_size">common language effect size</a> or <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#Rank-biserial_correla=
tion">rank-biserial correlation</a>).</li>
<li>The sample sizes</li>
<li>The significance level.</li></ul>
<p>In practice some of this information may already have been supplied and =
common sense should be used in deciding whether to repeat it. A typical rep=
ort might run,
</p>
<dl><dd>"Median latencies in groups E and C were 153 and 247 ms; the distri=
butions in the two groups differed significantly (Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml"><i>U</i> =3D 10.5</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n<=
/i><sub>1</sub> =3D <i>n</i><sub>2</sub> =3D 8</span>, <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>P</i> &lt; 0.05</span> two-tailed)."</dd></dl>
<p>A statement that does full justice to the statistical status of the test=
 might run,
</p>
<dl><dd>"Outcomes of the two treatments were compared using the Wilcoxon=E2=
=80=93Mann=E2=80=93Whitney two-sample rank-sum test. The treatment effect (=
difference between treatments) was quantified using the Hodges=E2=80=93Lehm=
ann (HL) estimator, which is consistent with the Wilcoxon test.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
nn%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This estimator (HL=CE=
=94) is the median of all possible differences in outcomes between a subjec=
t in group B and a subject in group&nbsp;A. A non-parametric 0.95 confidenc=
e interval for HL=CE=94 accompanies these estimates as does =CF=81, an esti=
mate of the probability that a randomly chosen subject from population B ha=
s a higher weight than a randomly chosen subject from population&nbsp;A. Th=
e median [quartiles] weight for subjects on treatment A and B respectively =
are 147 [121, 177] and 151 [130, 180] kg. Treatment A decreased weight by H=
L=CE=94 =3D 5 kg (0.95 CL [2, 9] kg, <span class=3D"texhtml">2<i>P</i> =3D =
0.02</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=81</i> =3D 0.58</span>)."</dd><=
/dl>
<p>However it would be rare to find such an extensive report in a document =
whose major topic was not statistical inference.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Normal_approximation_and_ti=
e_correction">Normal approximation and tie correction</h2><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: Normal approximation a=
nd tie correction"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brack=
et">]</span></span></div>
<p>For large samples, <i>U</i> is approximately <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normally d=
istributed</a>. In that case, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Standard_score" title=3D"Standard score">standardized value</a>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e z=3D{\frac {U-m_{U}}{\sigma _{U}}},\,}">
