<p>where the left side is simply the variance and the right side is the adj=
ustment for ties,  <i>t</i><sub><i>k</i></sub> is the number of ties for th=
e <i>k</i>th rank, and <i>K</i> is the total number of unique ranks with ti=
es.
</p><p>A more computationally-efficient form with <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
i>n</i><sub>1</sub><i>n</i><sub>2</sub>/12</span> factored out is
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \sigma _{\text{ties}}=3D{\sqrt {{n_{1}n_{2} \over 12}\left((n+1)-{\sum _{=
k=3D1}^{K}(t_{k}^{3}-t_{k}) \over n(n-1)}\right)}},}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>=CF=83<!-- =CF=83 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mtext>ties</mtext>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mfrac>
                <mrow>
                  <msub>
                    <mi>n</mi>
                    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                      <mn>1</mn>
                    </mrow>
                  </msub>
                  <msub>
                    <mi>n</mi>
                    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                      <mn>2</mn>
                    </mrow>
                  </msub>
                </mrow>
                <mn>12</mn>
              </mfrac>
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              <mo>(</mo>
              <mrow>
                <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
                <mi>n</mi>
                <mo>+</mo>
                <mn>1</mn>
                <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
                <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mfrac>
                    <mrow>
                      <munderover>
                        <mo>=E2=88=91<!-- =E2=88=91 --></mo>
                        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                          <mi>k</mi>
                          <mo>=3D</mo>
                          <mn>1</mn>
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                          <mi>K</mi>
                        </mrow>
                      </munderover>
                      <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
                      <msubsup>
                        <mi>t</mi>
                        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                          <mi>k</mi>
                        </mrow>
                        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                          <mn>3</mn>
                        </mrow>
                      </msubsup>
                      <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                      <msub>
                        <mi>t</mi>
                        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                          <mi>k</mi>
                        </mrow>
                      </msub>
                      <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
                    </mrow>
                    <mrow>
                      <mi>n</mi>
                      <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
                      <mi>n</mi>
                      <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
                      <mn>1</mn>
                      <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
                    </mrow>
                  </mfrac>
                </mrow>
              </mrow>
              <mo>)</mo>
            </mrow>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \sigma _{\tex=
t{ties}}=3D{\sqrt {{n_{1}n_{2} \over 12}\left((n+1)-{\sum _{k=3D1}^{K}(t_{k=
}^{3}-t_{k}) \over n(n-1)}\right)}},}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/f12092a24328b2a40b76ce9509347cff02c2a80b" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -3.171ex; width:45.069ex; height:8.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \s=
igma _{\text{ties}}=3D{\sqrt {{n_{1}n_{2} \over 12}\left((n+1)-{\sum _{k=3D=
1}^{K}(t_{k}^{3}-t_{k}) \over n(n-1)}\right)}},}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =3D <i>n</i><sub>1</sub> + <i>n</=
i><sub>2</sub></span>.
</p><p>If the number of ties is small (and especially if there are no large=
 tie bands) ties can be ignored when doing calculations by hand. The comput=
er statistical packages will use the correctly adjusted formula as a matter=
 of routine.
</p><p>Note that since <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>U</i><sub>1</sub> + <i>U<=
/i><sub>2</sub> =3D <i>n</i><sub>1</sub><i>n</i><sub>2</sub></span>, the me=
an <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i><sub>1</sub><i>n</i><sub>2</sub>/2</span=
> used in the normal approximation is the mean of the two values of <i>U</i=
>. Therefore, the absolute value of the <i>z</i>-statistic calculated will =
be same whichever value of <i>U</i> is used.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Effect_sizes">Effect sizes<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMann%E2%80%9=
3Whitney_U_test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: =
Effect sizes"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p>It is a widely recommended practice for scientists to report an <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Effect_size" title=3D"Effect size">effect=
 size</a> for an inferential test.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Wilkinson1999_16-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Wh=
itney_U_test#cite_note-Wilkinson1999-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Nak=
agawa2007_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-Nakagawa2007-17"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Proportion_of_concordance_o=
ut_of_all_pairs">Proportion of concordance out of all pairs</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_tes=
t&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Proportion of =
concordance out of all pairs"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The following measures are equivalent.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Common_language_effect_size=
">Common language effect size</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DMann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Common language effect size"><span>edit</span=
></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>One method of reporting the effect size for the Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>=
U</i> test is with <i>f</i>, the common language effect size.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-Kerby2014_18-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-Kerby2014-18"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-McGraw1992_19-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-McGraw1992-19"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> As a sample statistic, the common language effect size is computed=
 by forming all possible pairs between the two groups, then finding the pro=
portion of pairs that support a direction (say, that items from group 1 are=
 larger than items from group 2).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-McGraw1992_19-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitne=
y_U_test#cite_note-McGraw1992-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> To illustrate, in a study wit=
h a sample of ten hares and ten tortoises, the total number of ordered pair=
s is ten times ten or 100 pairs of hares and tortoises. Suppose the results=
 show that the hare ran faster than the tortoise in 90 of the 100 sample pa=
irs; in that case, the sample common language effect size is 90%.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The relationship between <i>f</i> and the Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U<=
/i> (specifically <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline">=
<span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"displa=
y: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle U_{1}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>U</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle U_{1}}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/bc9e7f892894bc50c32ce1b9f9a68a15562146ac" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:2.642ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle U_{=
1}}"></span>) is as follows:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e f=3D{U_{1} \over n_{1}n_{2}}\,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>f</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <msub>
              <mi>U</mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>1</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msub>
            <mrow>
              <msub>
                <mi>n</mi>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>1</mn>
                </mrow>
              </msub>
              <msub>
                <mi>n</mi>
                <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                  <mn>2</mn>
                </mrow>
              </msub>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle f=3D{U_{1} \o=
ver n_{1}n_{2}}\,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/20c4fab612698242b1afd7a21c8e1ef78f35e118" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.171ex; width:10.498ex; height:5.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle f=
=3D{U_{1} \over n_{1}n_{2}}\,}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>This is the same as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2=
%80%93Whitney_U_test#Area-under-curve_(AUC)_statistic_for_ROC_curves">area =
under the curve (AUC) for the ROC curve</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"=CF=81_statistic"><span id=
=3D".CF.81_statistic"></span><i>=CF=81</i> statistic</h4><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: =CF=81 statistic"><spa=
n>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></di=
v>
<p>A statistic called <i>=CF=81</i> that is linearly related to <i>U</i> an=
d widely used in studies of categorization (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Discrimination_learning" title=3D"Discrimination learning">discri=
mination learning</a> involving <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Co=
ncept" title=3D"Concept">concepts</a>), and elsewhere,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-H=
1976_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Man=
n%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-H1976-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> is calculated by d=
ividing <i>U</i> by its maximum value for the given sample sizes, which is =
simply <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i><sub>1</sub>=C3=97<i>n</i><sub>2</su=
b></span>. <i>=CF=81</i> is thus a non-parametric measure of the overlap be=
tween two distributions; it can take values between 0 and 1, and it estimat=
es <span class=3D"texhtml">P(<i>Y</i> &gt; <i>X</i>) + 0.5 P(<i>Y</i> =3D <=
i>X</i>)</span>, where <i>X</i> and <i>Y</i> are randomly chosen observatio=
ns from the two distributions. Both extreme values represent complete separ=
ation of the distributions, while a <i>=CF=81</i> of 0.5 represents complet=
e overlap. The usefulness of the <i>=CF=81</i> statistic can be seen in the=
 case of the odd example used above, where two distributions that were sign=
ificantly different on a Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test nonetheless had=
 nearly identical medians: the <i>=CF=81</i> value in this case is approxim=
ately 0.723 in favour of the hares, correctly reflecting the fact that even=
 though the median tortoise beat the median hare, the hares collectively di=
d better than the tortoises collectively.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Templ=
ate Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation n=
eeded"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (Feb=
ruary 2012)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Rank-biserial_correlation">=
Rank-biserial correlation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DMann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1=
4" title=3D"Edit section: Rank-biserial correlation"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A method of reporting the effect size for the Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U<=
/i> test is with a measure of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rank=
_correlation" title=3D"Rank correlation">rank correlation</a> known as the =
rank-biserial correlation. Edward Cureton introduced and named the measure.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Like other =
correlational measures, the rank-biserial correlation can range from minus =
one to plus one, with a value of zero indicating no relationship.
</p><p>There is a simple difference formula to compute the rank-biserial co=
rrelation from the common language effect size: the correlation is the diff=
erence between the proportion of pairs favorable to the hypothesis (<i>f</i=
>) minus its complement (i.e.: the proportion that is unfavorable (<i>u</i>=
)). This simple difference formula is just the difference of the common lan=
guage effect size of each group, and is as follows:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kerb=
y2014_18-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
nn%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-Kerby2014-18"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e r=3Df-u}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>r</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>f</mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>u</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle r=3Df-u}</ann=
otation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/ba01457a01266b4e82c4b5cb1c58740c2db03e8a" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:9.596ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle r=
=3Df-u}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>For example, consider the example where hares run faster than tortoises =
in 90 of 100 pairs. The common language effect size is 90%, so the rank-bis=
erial correlation is 90% minus 10%, and the rank-biserial&nbsp;<span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i> =3D 0.80</span>.
</p><p>An alternative formula for the rank-biserial can be used to calculat=
e it from the Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> (either <span class=3D"mwe-math=
-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe=
-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.or=
g/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle U_{1}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>U</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle U_{1}}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/bc9e7f892894bc50c32ce1b9f9a68a15562146ac" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:2.642ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle U_{=
1}}"></span> or <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><s=
pan class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display:=
 none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\dis=
playstyle U_{2}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>U</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle U_{2}}</annot=
ation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/590fa6a550fbe2866a28243a733d54245d218b9d" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:2.642ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle U_{=
2}}"></span>) and the sample sizes of each group:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whi=
tney_U_test#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e r=3Df-(1-f)=3D2f-1=3D{2U_{1} \over n_{1}n_{2}}-1=3D1-{2U_{2} \over n_{1}n=
_{2}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>r</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>f</mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mn>1</mn>
