<p>This formula is useful when the data are not available, but when there i=
s a published report, because <i>U</i> and the sample sizes are routinely r=
eported. Using the example above with 90 pairs that favor the hares and 10 =
pairs that favor the tortoise, <i>U</i><sub>2</sub> is the smaller of the t=
wo, so <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>U<sub>2</sub></i> =3D 10</span>. This for=
mula then gives <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>r</i> =3D 1 =E2=80=93 (2=C3=9710=
) / (10=C3=9710) =3D 0.80</span>, which is the same result as with the simp=
le difference formula above.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Relation_to_other_tests">Re=
lation to other tests</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DMann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" t=
itle=3D"Edit section: Relation to other tests"><span>edit</span></a><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Comparison_to_Student's_t-t=
est"><span id=3D"Comparison_to_Student.27s_t-test"></span>Comparison to Stu=
dent's <i>t</i>-test</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php=
?title=3DMann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" ti=
tle=3D"Edit section: Comparison to Student's t-test"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test tests a null hypothesis that the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_distribution" title=3D=
"Probability distribution">probability distribution</a> of a randomly drawn=
 observation from one group is the same as the probability distribution of =
a randomly drawn observation from the other group against an alternative th=
at those distributions are not equal (see <a class=3D"mw-selflink-fragment"=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#Assumpti=
ons_and_formal_statement_of_hypotheses">Mann=E2=80=93Whitney U test#Assumpt=
ions and formal statement of hypotheses</a>). In contrast, a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/T-test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"T-test">t=
-test</a> tests a null hypothesis of equal means in two groups against an a=
lternative of unequal means. Hence, except in special cases, the Mann=E2=80=
=93Whitney <i>U</i> test and the t-test do not test the same hypotheses and=
 should be compared with this in mind. =20
</p>
<dl><dt>Ordinal data</dt>
<dd>The Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test is preferable to the <i>t</i>-te=
st when the data are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Level_of_meas=
urement#Ordinal_scale" title=3D"Level of measurement">ordinal</a> but not i=
nterval scaled, in which case the spacing between adjacent values of the sc=
ale cannot be assumed to be constant.</dd>
<dt>Robustness</dt>
<dd>As it compares the sums of ranks,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Motulsky_2007_24-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%9=
3Whitney_U_test#cite_note-Motulsky_2007-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> the Mann=E2=80=93Wh=
itney <i>U</i> test is less likely than the <i>t</i>-test to spuriously ind=
icate significance because of the presence of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Outlier" title=3D"Outlier">outliers</a>. However, the Mann=E2=
=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test may have worse <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Type_I_and_type_II_errors" title=3D"Type I and type II errors">typ=
e I error</a> control when data are both heteroscedastic and non-normal.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></dd>
<dt>Efficiency</dt>
<dd>When normality holds, the Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test has an (as=
ymptotic) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Efficiency_(statistics)"=
 title=3D"Efficiency (statistics)">efficiency</a> of 3/<span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span> or about&nbsp;0.95 when=
 compared to the <i>t</i>-test.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Lehmann_1999_26-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitne=
y_U_test#cite_note-Lehmann_1999-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For distributions sufficien=
tly far from normal and for sufficiently large sample sizes, the Mann=E2=80=
=93Whitney <i>U</i> test is considerably more efficient than the <i>t</i>.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-Conover_1980_27-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-Conover_1980-=
27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> This comparison in efficiency, however, should be interpret=
ed with caution, as Mann=E2=80=93Whitney and the t-test do not test the sam=
e quantities. If, for example, a difference of group means is of primary in=
terest, Mann=E2=80=93Whitney is not an appropriate test.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%8=
0%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></dd></dl>
<p>The Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test will give very similar results to=
 performing an ordinary parametric two-sample <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/T_test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"T test"><i>t</i>-test</a=
> on the rankings of the data.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_no=
te-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p>
