<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Alternatives">Alternatives<=
/h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMann%E2%80%9=
3Whitney_U_test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: =
Alternatives"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p>If one desires a simple shift interpretation, the Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <=
i>U</i> test should <i>not</i> be used when the distributions of the two sa=
mples are very different, as it can give erroneous interpretation of signif=
icant results.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-33"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> In that situation, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Welch%27=
s_t-test" title=3D"Welch's t-test">unequal variances</a> version of the <i>=
t</i>-test may give more reliable results.
</p><p>Similarly, some authors (<cite id=3D"CITEREFConover1999" class=3D"ci=
tation book cs1">Conover, W. J. (1999). <i>Practical Nonparametric Statisti=
cs -- 3rd ed</i>. New York: John Wiley &amp; Sons. p.&nbsp;272-281. <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-471-16068-7" title=3D"Special:BookSources/0-4=
71-16068-7"><bdi>0-471-16068-7</bdi></a>.</cite><span title=3D"ctx_ver=3DZ3=
9.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=3Dinfo%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.gen=
re=3Dbook&amp;rft.btitle=3DPractical+Nonparametric+Statistics+--+3rd+ed.&am=
p;rft.place=3DNew+York&amp;rft.pages=3D272-281&amp;rft.pub=3DJohn+Wiley+%26=
+Sons&amp;rft.date=3D1999&amp;rft.isbn=3D0-471-16068-7&amp;rft.aulast=3DCon=
over&amp;rft.aufirst=3DW.+J.&amp;rfr_id=3Dinfo%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AM=
ann%E2%80%93Whitney+U+test" class=3D"Z3988"></span>) suggest transforming t=
he data to ranks (if they are not already ranks) and then performing the <i=
>t</i>-test on the transformed data, the version of the <i>t</i>-test used =
depending on whether or not the population variances are suspected to be di=
fferent. Rank transformations do not preserve variances, but variances are =
recomputed from samples after rank transformations.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brown%E2%80%93Forsythe_=
test" title=3D"Brown=E2=80=93Forsythe test">Brown=E2=80=93Forsythe test</a>=
 has been suggested as an appropriate non-parametric equivalent to the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F-test" title=3D"F-test"><i>F</i>-test=
</a> for equal variances.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fac=
t" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span tit=
le=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2012)">cit=
ation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>A more powerful test is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Brunner_Munzel_Test" title=3D"Brunner Munzel Test">Brunner-Munzel test</a>=
, outperforming the Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test in case of violated =
assumption of exchangeability.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_no=
te-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test is a special case of the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proportional_odds_model" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Proportional odds model">proportional odds model</a>, all=
owing for covariate-adjustment.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_n=
ote-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>See also <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kolmogorov%E2%80%9=
3Smirnov_test" title=3D"Kolmogorov=E2=80=93Smirnov test">Kolmogorov=E2=80=
=93Smirnov test</a>.
</p>
