<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMann%E2%80%93Whitney_U=
_test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section: History"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>The statistic appeared in a 1914 article<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kruskal57_40=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80=
%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-Kruskal57-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> by the German Gustav =
Deuchler (with a missing term in the variance).
</p><p>In a single paper in 1945, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Frank_Wilcoxon" title=3D"Frank Wilcoxon">Frank Wilcoxon</a> proposed <sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-wilcoxon1945_41-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-wilcoxon1945-41"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> both the one-sample signed rank and the two-sample rank sum test=
, in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Test_of_significance" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Test of significance">test of significance</a> wi=
th a point null-hypothesis against its complementary alternative (that is, =
equal versus not equal). However, he only tabulated a few points for the eq=
ual-sample size case in that paper (though in a later paper he gave larger =
tables).
</p><p>A thorough analysis of the statistic, which included a recurrence al=
lowing the computation of tail probabilities for arbitrary sample sizes and=
 tables for sample sizes of eight or less appeared in the article by <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Mann" title=3D"Henry Mann">Henry M=
ann</a> and his student Donald Ransom Whitney in 1947.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-m=
annwhitney1947_1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test#cite_note-mannwhitney1947-1"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
This article discussed alternative hypotheses, including a <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stochastic_ordering" title=3D"Stochastic ordering"=
>stochastic ordering</a> (where the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Cumulative_distribution_function" title=3D"Cumulative distribution functi=
on">cumulative distribution functions</a> satisfied the pointwise inequalit=
y <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>F</i><sub><i>X</i></sub>(<i>t</i>) &lt; <i>F</=
i><sub><i>Y</i></sub>(<i>t</i>)</span>). This paper also computed the first=
 four moments and established the limiting normality of the statistic under=
 the null hypothesis, so establishing that it is asymptotically distributio=
n-free.
</p>
